Task 6: Automating Backups with Shell Scripting 🤖
🔄 System Automation and Cron Scheduling

Project Overview
Manual backups are prone to human error. In this task, I developed a Bash script to automate the backup of the /devops_workspace directory. I also configured a cron job to ensure the system handles backups automatically at scheduled intervals.

---

Step-by-Step Implementation
1 Create the Backup Directory
Bash
sudo mkdir -p /backups

---

2 Write the Shell Script
I created a script named backup.sh that compresses files and uses a dynamic timestamp for the filename.
Bash

#!/bin/bash

# Variables
SOURCE_DIR="/devops_workspace"
BACKUP_DIR="/backups"
TIMESTAMP=$(date +%F_%H-%M-%S)
FILENAME="backup_$TIMESTAMP.tar.gz"

# Create the backup
tar -czf $BACKUP_DIR/$FILENAME $SOURCE_DIR

# Display success message in Green
echo -e "\e[32m✅ Success: Backup created at $BACKUP_DIR/$FILENAME\e[0m"

---

3 Set Executive Permissions
For the script to run, it needs execution rights.
Bash
chmod +x backup.sh

---

4 Automate with Cron
I scheduled the script to run every day at midnight.
Bash
crontab -e
# Add this line at the bottom:
0 0 * * * /path/to/your/backup.sh

---

Key Concepts Learned

Variables: Using SOURCE_DIR and TIMESTAMP to make scripts reusable.

Tar: Compressing files to save storage space.

Echo Colors: Using escape codes (\e[32m) to make terminal output user-friendly.

Cron: The Linux time-based job scheduler.

